// ── PASSAGE 1: Financial Inclusion & PMJDY ──
const RC1 = `Financial inclusion has emerged as a cornerstone of India's developmental agenda. The Pradhan Mantri Jan Dhan Yojana (PMJDY), launched in August 2014, is the world's largest financial inclusion initiative. It aims to ensure access to financial services — savings accounts, remittance, credit, insurance, and pension — for the excluded sections of society at an affordable cost. Under this scheme, every household is entitled to at least one bank account, a RuPay debit card with an inbuilt accident insurance cover of Rs.2 lakh, and an overdraft facility of up to Rs.10,000 for eligible account holders. By 2024, the scheme had opened over 53 crore accounts, with women holding more than 55% of these accounts. The Direct Benefit Transfer (DBT) mechanism, linked with PMJDY accounts, has prevented leakages worth thousands of crores. The scheme also promotes digital literacy, helping rural populations transition from cash-based to digital transactions. Despite challenges such as dormant accounts, low average balances, and limited credit uptake, PMJDY remains a transformative milestone in banking the unbanked.`;

Q.push(
{id:'rc1_1',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC1}\n\nQ: According to the passage, which of the following is NOT a financial service offered under PMJDY?`,o:['Savings account and remittance','Accident insurance cover via RuPay card','Home loan at subsidised interest rates','Overdraft facility up to Rs.10,000'],c:2,e:'The passage lists savings accounts, remittance, credit, insurance, pension, RuPay debit card with accident insurance of Rs.2 lakh, and overdraft facility — but makes no mention of home loans at subsidised interest rates. Hence option C is not mentioned.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1','sbi_prelims']},

{id:'rc1_2',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC1}\n\nQ: What does the passage identify as the primary purpose of the Direct Benefit Transfer mechanism linked with PMJDY?`,o:['To promote digital literacy in rural areas','To provide accident insurance to account holders','To prevent leakages of government funds','To increase the number of bank accounts opened'],c:2,e:'The passage states: "The Direct Benefit Transfer (DBT) mechanism, linked with PMJDY accounts, has prevented leakages worth thousands of crores." This directly answers the question — the primary purpose is to prevent fund leakages.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1','sbi_prelims']},

{id:'rc1_3',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'easy',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC1}\n\nQ: What percentage of PMJDY accounts are held by women, as stated in the passage?`,o:['More than 45%','More than 50%','More than 55%','Exactly 60%'],c:2,e:'The passage clearly states "women holding more than 55% of these accounts." Option C is directly supported by the text.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'rc1_4',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC1}\n\nQ: Which of the following challenges to PMJDY is mentioned in the passage?`,o:['Lack of government support and funding','Dormant accounts and low average balances','Absence of RuPay network in rural areas','Inadequate overdraft limits for farmers'],c:1,e:'The passage mentions "challenges such as dormant accounts, low average balances, and limited credit uptake." Option B correctly identifies two of these challenges. The other options are not mentioned in the passage.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc1_5',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC1}\n\nQ: The author's tone towards PMJDY can best be described as:`,o:['Highly critical and dismissive','Completely neutral and factual','Balanced — acknowledging both achievements and challenges','Enthusiastically promotional without any reservations'],c:2,e:'The author presents significant achievements (53 crore accounts, DBT linkage, women empowerment) but also acknowledges challenges (dormant accounts, low balances, limited credit uptake). This balanced perspective makes option C the most accurate description of the author\'s tone.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ── PASSAGE 2: UPI & Digital Payments ──
const RC2 = `The Unified Payments Interface (UPI) has revolutionised the digital payments landscape in India, positioning the country as a global leader in real-time payment systems. Developed by the National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) and launched in 2016, UPI enables instant interbank transfers using a Virtual Payment Address (VPA) without the need to share sensitive bank details. By 2024, UPI was processing over 13 billion transactions per month, with a total annual value exceeding Rs.200 lakh crore. The ecosystem includes apps like PhonePe, Google Pay, Paytm, and the government-backed BHIM. A significant policy milestone was the introduction of UPI123Pay for feature phone users, and UPI Lite for small offline transactions, extending digital payments to those without smartphones or reliable internet. India has also exported UPI to countries like Singapore, UAE, France, and Bhutan, enhancing cross-border remittance capabilities. The RBI's tokenisation framework and the interoperability mandate have further strengthened consumer trust. Critics, however, point to zero MDR (Merchant Discount Rate) as a potential barrier to long-term sustainability of payment service providers.`;

Q.push(
{id:'rc2_1',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'easy',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC2}\n\nQ: Which organisation developed UPI, as mentioned in the passage?`,o:['Reserve Bank of India (RBI)','Ministry of Finance','National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI)','State Bank of India'],c:2,e:'The passage explicitly states "Developed by the National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI)." RBI regulates but did not develop UPI directly.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc2_2',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC2}\n\nQ: UPI123Pay was introduced specifically to benefit which group of users?`,o:['Users without a bank account','Feature phone users without smartphones','Merchants with large transaction volumes','NRIs sending money from abroad'],c:1,e:'The passage states "the introduction of UPI123Pay for feature phone users" — this was specifically to extend digital payment access to those who do not have smartphones.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc2_3',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC2}\n\nQ: Which of the following countries is NOT mentioned in the passage as a nation to which India has exported UPI?`,o:['Singapore','UAE','Japan','Bhutan'],c:2,e:'The passage mentions Singapore, UAE, France, and Bhutan as countries where UPI has been exported. Japan is not mentioned anywhere in the passage.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'rc2_4',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC2}\n\nQ: What concern do critics raise about UPI's ecosystem, according to the passage?`,o:['UPI transactions are not secure for large amounts','Zero MDR may harm long-term sustainability of payment providers','Feature phone users cannot access UPI services','Cross-border UPI transfers attract high charges'],c:1,e:'The passage states "Critics, however, point to zero MDR (Merchant Discount Rate) as a potential barrier to long-term sustainability of payment service providers." Zero MDR means merchants are not charged, reducing revenue for payment companies.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc2_5',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC2}\n\nQ: The word 'interoperability' as used in the passage most nearly means:`,o:['The ability of different systems to work together seamlessly','The process of encrypting payment data for security','A government mandate requiring fee-free transactions','The system of virtual payment addresses'],c:0,e:'"Interoperability" refers to the capability of different systems, platforms, or applications to communicate and work together. In the context of UPI, it means different payment apps and banks can transact with each other without barriers.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ── PASSAGE 3: Non-Performing Assets & Banking Reforms ──
const RC3 = `Non-Performing Assets (NPAs) represent one of the most critical challenges confronting the Indian banking system. An asset becomes non-performing when the borrower fails to service the loan — either interest or principal — for more than 90 days. Gross NPAs of scheduled commercial banks peaked at approximately Rs.10.36 lakh crore in 2018, accounting for 11.6% of total advances. The government and the RBI undertook a series of structural reforms to address this crisis. The Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC), enacted in 2016, established a time-bound resolution framework, replacing the earlier slow-moving debt recovery mechanisms. Asset Quality Review (AQR) initiated by the RBI in 2015 forced banks to recognise hidden NPAs, resulting in a short-term spike in reported bad loans but providing a truer picture of banking health. Recapitalisation of public sector banks, consolidation of weaker banks with stronger ones, and the establishment of the National Asset Reconstruction Company Ltd (NARCL) — commonly called the 'bad bank' — represent further reform measures. By 2023, gross NPAs had declined to around 3.9%, signalling significant improvement, though concerns about restructured loans and evergreening of accounts persist.`;

Q.push(
{id:'rc3_1',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'easy',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC3}\n\nQ: According to the passage, an asset is classified as non-performing when the borrower fails to service the loan for more than:`,o:['60 days','90 days','120 days','180 days'],c:1,e:'The passage explicitly states "when the borrower fails to service the loan — either interest or principal — for more than 90 days." This is the standard RBI definition of an NPA.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc3_2',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC3}\n\nQ: What was the immediate effect of the Asset Quality Review (AQR) initiated by RBI in 2015?`,o:['Immediate reduction in gross NPAs across all banks','A short-term spike in reported bad loans','Consolidation of public sector banks','Enactment of the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code'],c:1,e:'The passage states AQR "forced banks to recognise hidden NPAs, resulting in a short-term spike in reported bad loans but providing a truer picture of banking health." The spike was a short-term consequence of recognising previously hidden NPAs.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc3_3',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC3}\n\nQ: NARCL is referred to in the passage as:`,o:['A debt recovery tribunal','A credit rating agency','A bad bank','A special purpose vehicle for bank mergers'],c:2,e:'The passage states "the establishment of the National Asset Reconstruction Company Ltd (NARCL) — commonly called the \'bad bank\'." This is the term used in the passage to describe NARCL.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc3_4',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC3}\n\nQ: Which of the following best describes the significance of the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC) as explained in the passage?`,o:['It recapitalised public sector banks with government funds','It replaced slow debt recovery mechanisms with a time-bound resolution framework','It merged weak banks with stronger public sector banks','It mandated banks to disclose NPAs quarterly to the RBI'],c:1,e:'The passage says the IBC "established a time-bound resolution framework, replacing the earlier slow-moving debt recovery mechanisms." This is the key significance of IBC highlighted in the passage.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc3_5',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC3}\n\nQ: What does the phrase "evergreening of accounts" most likely refer to in the context of the passage?`,o:['Maintaining a positive balance in savings accounts year-round','The practice of granting fresh loans to repay old loans, masking bad debts','Converting foreign currency loans to rupee-denominated loans','The process of upgrading non-performing accounts to standard status'],c:1,e:'"Evergreening" is a banking term for the practice where banks extend new credit to a defaulting borrower to help repay old dues, thereby avoiding NPA classification. The passage uses it alongside "restructured loans" as a persistent concern even after NPA improvement.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ── PASSAGE 4: Monetary Policy & Inflation ──
const RC4 = `Monetary policy is the mechanism by which a central bank, such as the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), controls the money supply and interest rates to achieve macroeconomic objectives — primarily price stability and growth. The Monetary Policy Committee (MPC), constituted in 2016 under the amended RBI Act, is a six-member body responsible for setting the policy repo rate. The MPC comprises three RBI officials, including the Governor who chairs it, and three external members appointed by the government. The inflation-targeting framework, adopted in 2016, mandates the MPC to maintain Consumer Price Index (CPI) inflation at 4%, with a tolerance band of ±2%. If inflation remains outside this band for three consecutive quarters, the RBI must submit a report to the government explaining the reasons and remedial measures. Key policy instruments include the repo rate (rate at which RBI lends to banks), the reverse repo rate (rate at which RBI absorbs liquidity from banks), the Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR), and the Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR). Food inflation, particularly driven by vegetable price volatility, remains a recurring challenge for meeting the inflation target in India.`;

Q.push(
{id:'rc4_1',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'easy',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC4}\n\nQ: How many members does the Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) comprise, according to the passage?`,o:['Three members','Four members','Six members','Eight members'],c:2,e:'The passage states "a six-member body" — the MPC has six members in total: three RBI officials and three external members appointed by the government.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc4_2',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC4}\n\nQ: According to the inflation-targeting framework described in the passage, what action must the RBI take if inflation stays outside the tolerance band for three consecutive quarters?`,o:['Immediately raise the repo rate by 50 basis points','Impose emergency CRR restrictions on all banks','Submit a report to the government explaining reasons and remedial measures','Convene an emergency MPC meeting within 15 days'],c:2,e:'The passage explicitly states "the RBI must submit a report to the government explaining the reasons and remedial measures" if inflation stays outside the ±2% band for three consecutive quarters.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc4_3',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC4}\n\nQ: The reverse repo rate, as defined in the passage, is:`,o:['The rate at which RBI lends money to commercial banks','The rate at which banks borrow from each other overnight','The rate at which RBI absorbs liquidity from banks','The minimum rate banks must charge on retail loans'],c:2,e:'The passage defines reverse repo rate as "rate at which RBI absorbs liquidity from banks." When banks park excess funds with RBI, RBI pays this rate to them.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc4_4',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC4}\n\nQ: What does the passage identify as a recurring challenge for meeting India's inflation target?`,o:['Volatile crude oil prices and global commodity shocks','Food inflation driven by vegetable price volatility','Depreciation of the Indian Rupee against the US Dollar','High fiscal deficit leading to excess money supply'],c:1,e:'The passage concludes: "Food inflation, particularly driven by vegetable price volatility, remains a recurring challenge for meeting the inflation target in India." This is directly stated.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc4_5',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC4}\n\nQ: Which of the following inferences can be validly drawn from the passage?`,o:['The MPC has the authority to override the RBI Governor on rate decisions','The inflation target of 4% has never been breached since 2016','External members of the MPC are drawn from the finance ministry only','The inflation-targeting framework was introduced as part of an amendment to the RBI Act'],c:3,e:'The passage states "The Monetary Policy Committee (MPC), constituted in 2016 under the amended RBI Act." This confirms that the framework was introduced via an amendment to the RBI Act. Option A is wrong (voting procedure is not discussed), B is wrong (the passage mentions the band tolerance implying breaches are possible), and C is wrong (the passage says "government" appoints them, not specifically finance ministry).',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ── PASSAGE 5: MSME Sector ──
const RC5 = `Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises (MSMEs) form the backbone of India's economy, contributing approximately 30% to the GDP, over 45% to exports, and providing employment to more than 11 crore people. Revised classification criteria introduced in 2020 redefined MSMEs based on both investment in plant and machinery and annual turnover, replacing the earlier single-criterion approach. A micro enterprise now has an investment limit of up to Rs.1 crore and a turnover of up to Rs.5 crore. Despite their significance, MSMEs face structural challenges: limited access to formal credit, technological backwardness, infrastructure deficiencies, and vulnerability to global supply chain disruptions. The Emergency Credit Line Guarantee Scheme (ECLGS), launched during the COVID-19 pandemic, provided guaranteed credit to stressed MSMEs, disbursing over Rs.3.6 lakh crore. The MSME Samadhaan portal enables online filing of delayed payment complaints. Delayed payment by large corporates and government departments remains a systemic issue — MSMEs are legally entitled to payment within 45 days under the MSMED Act. The Udyam Registration portal has simplified MSME formalisation. Despite policy support, many micro enterprises remain in the informal economy, limiting their access to institutional finance and social security benefits.`;

Q.push(
{id:'rc5_1',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'easy',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC5}\n\nQ: According to the passage, what is the employment provided by the MSME sector?`,o:['More than 5 crore people','More than 8 crore people','More than 11 crore people','More than 15 crore people'],c:2,e:'The passage states "providing employment to more than 11 crore people." This figure refers to total direct employment generated by the MSME sector.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc5_2',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC5}\n\nQ: What was the key change introduced by the revised MSME classification criteria of 2020?`,o:['MSMEs were reclassified based solely on number of employees','The single-criterion approach was replaced by a dual criterion of investment and turnover','The investment limit for all categories was doubled uniformly','A new category of "super-micro" enterprises was introduced'],c:1,e:'The passage states "Revised classification criteria introduced in 2020 redefined MSMEs based on both investment in plant and machinery and annual turnover, replacing the earlier single-criterion approach." The key change was moving from a single criterion to a dual criterion.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc5_3',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC5}\n\nQ: The MSME Samadhaan portal, as described in the passage, is used for:`,o:['Online MSME registration and formalisation','Accessing emergency credit guarantees during crises','Filing delayed payment complaints online','Tracking export performance of MSME units'],c:2,e:'The passage states "The MSME Samadhaan portal enables online filing of delayed payment complaints." Udyam Registration handles formalisation; ECLGS handles emergency credit — these are separate mechanisms.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'rc5_4',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC5}\n\nQ: Under the MSMED Act, within how many days are large corporates legally required to pay MSMEs?`,o:['30 days','45 days','60 days','90 days'],c:1,e:'The passage explicitly states "MSMEs are legally entitled to payment within 45 days under the MSMED Act." Delayed payment beyond this period is a systemic problem the passage highlights.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc5_5',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC5}\n\nQ: Which of the following best explains why many micro enterprises remain outside the institutional finance system, as suggested by the passage?`,o:['They deliberately avoid formal registration to evade taxes','They prefer informal money-lenders who offer lower interest rates','Many remain in the informal economy, limiting access to institutional finance','The government has not created any specific portals for their registration'],c:2,e:'The passage concludes: "many micro enterprises remain in the informal economy, limiting their access to institutional finance and social security benefits." Operating informally means they lack the documentation and formal status needed to access bank credit.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ── PASSAGE 6: Green Finance & Sustainable Banking ──
const RC6 = `Green finance refers to financial instruments and services that support environmentally sustainable economic activities and projects that mitigate climate change. In India, the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) introduced the Green Bond framework in 2023, building on existing regulations to align with international standards such as the International Capital Market Association (ICMA) Green Bond Principles. The Reserve Bank of India has incorporated climate risk into the financial stability assessment framework, acknowledging that physical and transition risks from climate change pose systemic threats to banks' asset quality. In 2023, the government issued Sovereign Green Bonds worth Rs.16,000 crore to fund green infrastructure projects, including solar energy, clean transportation, and energy efficiency. The Business Responsibility and Sustainability Report (BRSR) mandated by SEBI for listed companies ensures transparency in ESG (Environmental, Social, and Governance) disclosures. Internationally, the concept of 'stranded assets' — fossil fuel assets that may lose value due to climate regulations — is increasingly factoring into bank lending decisions. Despite growing momentum, challenges include the absence of a unified green taxonomy in India, greenwashing risks, and limited capacity of banks to assess climate-related financial risks. Sustainable finance presents an enormous opportunity for India to mobilise capital towards its net-zero commitments.`;

Q.push(
{id:'rc6_1',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'easy',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC6}\n\nQ: What does ESG stand for, as mentioned in the passage?`,o:['Economic, Social and Governance','Environmental, Social and Governance','Environmental, Sustainability and Growth','Equity, Social and Green'],c:1,e:'The passage explicitly states "ESG (Environmental, Social, and Governance) disclosures." ESG is a standard framework for evaluating a company\'s impact and risks across these three dimensions.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc6_2',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC6}\n\nQ: For what total value did the Government of India issue Sovereign Green Bonds in 2023?`,o:['Rs.8,000 crore','Rs.10,000 crore','Rs.16,000 crore','Rs.20,000 crore'],c:2,e:'The passage states "the government issued Sovereign Green Bonds worth Rs.16,000 crore to fund green infrastructure projects." This figure is directly mentioned.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'rc6_3',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'medium',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC6}\n\nQ: The term 'stranded assets' as used in the passage refers to:`,o:['Bank loans that have become non-performing assets','Green bonds that cannot find buyers in the market','Fossil fuel assets that may lose value due to climate regulations','Infrastructure projects abandoned due to environmental protests'],c:2,e:'The passage defines stranded assets as "fossil fuel assets that may lose value due to climate regulations." As the world transitions away from fossil fuels, such assets risk becoming economically unviable.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc6_4',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC6}\n\nQ: Which of the following challenges to green finance in India is mentioned in the passage?`,o:['Lack of investor interest in green bonds','Absence of a unified green taxonomy and greenwashing risks','RBI\'s refusal to incorporate climate risk in policy frameworks','SEBI has not introduced any green bond regulations'],c:1,e:'The passage states "challenges include the absence of a unified green taxonomy in India, greenwashing risks, and limited capacity of banks to assess climate-related financial risks." Option B directly matches two of these stated challenges.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'rc6_5',s:'english',t:'reading_comprehension',d:'hard',q:`Read the following passage carefully:\n\n${RC6}\n\nQ: What role does the Business Responsibility and Sustainability Report (BRSR) play, according to the passage?`,o:['It mandates green bond issuance by listed companies every year','It sets interest rate guidelines for sustainable project loans','It ensures transparency in ESG disclosures for listed companies','It replaces the Green Bond framework introduced by SEBI'],c:2,e:'The passage states BRSR is "mandated by SEBI for listed companies ensures transparency in ESG (Environmental, Social, and Governance) disclosures." Its function is disclosure and transparency, not bond issuance or interest rate setting.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

