Q.push(
{id:'ed1',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The committee have / (B) decided to postpone / (C) the meeting until / (D) further notice. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:0,e:'"The committee" is treated as a singular collective noun in formal/standard usage, so the verb should be "has decided," not "have decided." The error is in part A.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed2',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) Neither the manager / (B) nor the employees / (C) were present / (D) at the board meeting. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:3,e:'With "neither...nor," the verb agrees with the subject closest to it — "the employees" (plural), so "were" is correct. There is no grammatical error in this sentence. The answer is D (No error).',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed3',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The RBI has been / (B) implementing several / (C) measure to curb / (D) rising inflation. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'"Measure" should be "measures" (plural) because several is used, which always takes a plural noun. The error is in part C.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed4',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'hard',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) Had the government / (B) not intervened timely, / (C) the banking crisis / (D) would have worsened. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'"Timely" is an adjective, not an adverb. The correct adverb form is also "timely" in some usages, but in this context "in time" or "promptly" is more appropriate. However, the specific error is that "timely" here functions as an adjective used adverbially — the grammatically precise option is "in a timely manner." Part B contains the error.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed5',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'easy',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) Each of the students / (B) in the banking class / (C) are expected to / (D) submit their assignment. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'"Each" is singular and always takes a singular verb. The correct form is "is expected to," not "are expected to." The error is in part C.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed6',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The news about / (B) the bank mergers / (C) were shocking / (D) to the investors. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'"News" is an uncountable singular noun and always takes a singular verb. The correct form is "was shocking," not "were shocking." The error is in part C.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed7',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) Despite of his / (B) vast experience in / (C) banking, he failed / (D) the interview. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:0,e:'"Despite" is a preposition that does not take "of." The correct usage is simply "Despite his vast experience..." — "despite of" is grammatically incorrect. The error is in part A.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed8',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'hard',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The data collected / (B) by the survey team / (C) suggests a decline / (D) in rural savings. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'"Data" is the plural form of "datum." In formal/academic usage, it takes a plural verb: "suggest," not "suggests." The error is in part C. (Note: In informal usage "data" is sometimes treated as singular, but in exam English, plural agreement is preferred.)',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed9',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) He is one of / (B) those officers who / (C) has always performed / (D) beyond expectations. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'In "one of those + plural noun + who/that" constructions, the relative clause verb agrees with the plural noun, not "one." So it should be "have always performed," not "has always performed." The error is in part C.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed10',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'easy',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The bank will / (B) sanction the loan / (C) only if you will submit / (D) all required documents. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'In conditional sentences (Type 1), the "if" clause uses simple present tense, not future tense. Correct form: "only if you submit." Using "will submit" in the if-clause is grammatically incorrect. The error is in part C.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed11',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The number of / (B) unemployed youth / (C) are increasing / (D) year after year. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'"The number of" takes a singular verb — the focus is on "the number," which is singular. Correct form: "is increasing." (Note: "A number of" takes a plural verb, but "The number of" takes singular.) Error is in part C.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed12',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'hard',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The policy, along with / (B) its amendments, have been / (C) approved by the / (D) parliamentary committee. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'When a singular subject is followed by "along with," "as well as," or "together with," the verb agrees with the main subject, not the additional phrase. "The policy" is singular, so "has been approved" is correct, not "have been." Error is in part B.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed13',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) She has been / (B) working in this bank / (C) since the last / (D) five years. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'"Since" is used with a point in time (since 2010, since Monday). "For" is used with a period of time (for five years). The correct form is "for the last five years," not "since the last five years." Error is in part C.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed14',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The manager asked / (B) the clerk that / (C) why he was absent / (D) without prior intimation. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'In indirect speech with a "why" question, "that" should not be used before the question word. The correct form is "the manager asked the clerk why he was absent." "That" is redundant and incorrect before "why." Error is in part B.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed15',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'hard',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) It is imperative / (B) that every employee / (C) follows the new / (D) compliance guidelines. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'After "It is imperative that," the verb in the subordinate clause must be in the subjunctive mood (base form), not the indicative. Correct form: "that every employee follow the new compliance guidelines" — not "follows." Error is in part C.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed16',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) Scarcely had / (B) the RBI announced / (C) the rate cut when / (D) markets rallied sharply. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:3,e:'"Scarcely/Hardly/Barely" correctly pairs with "when" — not "than." The sentence "Scarcely had the RBI announced the rate cut when markets rallied sharply" is grammatically correct. There is no error. The answer is D (No error).',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed17',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'easy',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) Ram and Shyam / (B) is going to attend / (C) the banking seminar / (D) next Monday. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'"Ram and Shyam" is a compound subject (plural). It requires a plural verb: "are going to attend," not "is going to attend." Error is in part B.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed18',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'hard',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) No sooner did / (B) the Finance Minister announce / (C) the budget than / (D) share prices dropped. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:3,e:'The sentence uses "No sooner...than" correctly. "No sooner did the Finance Minister announce the budget than share prices dropped." This is grammatically correct. The answer is No Error (D — the last option).',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed19',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The inflation has / (B) risen by two percent / (C) in the last quarter / (D) of this fiscal. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:0,e:'"Has risen" in part A implies recent past action with present relevance, which is used correctly here. However, "the inflation" is incorrect — inflation as a general concept does not take the definite article "the." It should be "Inflation has risen." Error is in part A.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed20',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The robbers / (B) have fled away / (C) before the police / (D) arrived at the scene. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'"Fled" already implies moving away; "fled away" is redundant. The correct form is simply "had fled" (past perfect, since fleeing occurred before police arrived) — making both "away" and the tense in part B erroneous. The primary error is "fled away" (redundancy and tense) in part B.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed21',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'hard',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The RBI Governor, / (B) along with senior officials, / (C) were present at / (D) the G20 finance meet. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'When the subject "The RBI Governor" (singular) is followed by "along with senior officials," the verb agrees with the main subject. "Were present" should be "was present." Error is in part C.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed22',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) He denied / (B) that he had not / (C) taken any bribe / (D) from the contractor. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'"Denied" already carries a negative meaning. Adding "not" in "denied that he had not taken" creates a double negative that reverses the intended meaning. Correct form: "He denied that he had taken any bribe." Remove "not." Error is in part B.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed23',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'easy',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) My sister as well as / (B) my brothers / (C) are planning to / (D) join the banking sector. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:2,e:'"My sister" is the main subject; "as well as my brothers" is a parenthetical addition. The verb should agree with "my sister" (singular): "is planning," not "are planning." Error is in part C.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ed24',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'hard',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) The committee recommended / (B) that the manager should / (C) be suspended for / (D) gross misconduct. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'After verbs of recommendation, suggestion, demand, insistence, etc., the subjunctive mood is used: "that the manager BE suspended." Using "should be" is common but not the grammatically prescribed form in formal English. Error is in part B.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ed25',s:'english',t:'error_detection',d:'medium',q:'Identify the part of the sentence that has a grammatical error:\n\n(A) Two-thirds of the / (B) work have already / (C) been completed by / (D) the project team. / (E) No error',o:['A','B','C','D'],c:1,e:'In fractions, when the noun after "of" is uncountable or refers to a whole ("work"), the verb is singular. "Two-thirds of the work HAS already been completed" is correct. "Have" is incorrect. Error is in part B.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},
);

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// SENTENCE IMPROVEMENT (si1 to si20) — 20 questions
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Q.push(
{id:'si1',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe officer was asked to look [into] the matter as soon as possible.',o:['look over','look into','look after','look up'],c:1,e:'"Look into" means to investigate or examine, which is the correct phrasal verb when examining a matter. "Look over" means to review briefly; "look after" means to take care of; "look up" means to search for information. No change is needed — "look into" is already correct and option B preserves it.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si2',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe bank manager insisted that the new policy [will be implemented] from the next quarter.',o:['would be implemented','will be implemented','should have been implemented','has been implemented'],c:0,e:'After "insisted that" (a reporting verb expressing demand/insistence), the subordinate clause uses "would" (past modal) or subjunctive. Since the main verb "insisted" is past tense, "would be implemented" is the correct form for reported speech.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si3',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'easy',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nShe is [more smarter] than her colleagues in financial analysis.',o:['smartest','smarter','more smart','most smartest'],c:1,e:'"More smarter" is a double comparative error. "Smart" is a one-syllable adjective and forms comparatives with "-er": "smarter." Never use "more" with "-er" forms. "Smarter than" is the correct construction.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si4',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe finance ministry [has been announced] a new scheme for rural credit last week.',o:['announced','has announced','have announced','was announcing'],c:0,e:'"Last week" is a specific past time reference, so simple past tense must be used: "announced." Present perfect ("has been announced," "has announced") cannot be used with specific past time expressions like "last week," "yesterday," or "in 2020."',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si5',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'hard',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nNeither the Chairman nor the board members [was] willing to accept the audit findings.',o:['were','was','are being','have been'],c:0,e:'In "Neither...nor" constructions, the verb agrees with the subject closest to it — "board members" (plural). So the correct verb is "were," not "was." Option A is correct.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si6',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe accused [admitted committing] the fraud when confronted with evidence.',o:['admitted to commit','admitted committing','admitted to have committed','admitted having commit'],c:1,e:'"Admit" is followed by a gerund (verb+ing), not an infinitive. "Admitted committing" is correct. "Admitted to commit" is wrong (infinitive after "to" is possible only in "admit to" + gerund form). "Admitted committing" (option B) is the standard correct form.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si7',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'easy',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe government is working [hardly] to reduce unemployment in rural areas.',o:['hard','hardly','more harder','most hard'],c:0,e:'"Hard" functions both as an adjective and an adverb meaning "with great effort." "Hardly" is a different word meaning "scarcely" or "almost not." The sentence needs the adverb of intensity "hard" to mean working with great effort.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si8',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nBy the time the auditors arrived, the accounts [were already tampered] with.',o:['had already been tampered','were already tampered','have already been tampered','had already tampered'],c:0,e:'The action of tampering happened before the past action of auditors arriving — this requires past perfect passive: "had already been tampered with." "Were tampered" is simple past passive, which does not convey the chronological relationship correctly.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si9',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe economist suggested that India [should focuses] more on domestic demand.',o:['should focus','should focuses','must focuses','ought to focused'],c:0,e:'After modal verbs (should, must, will, etc.), the base form of the verb is used without "s" — "should focus," not "should focuses." Adding "s" after a modal verb is a common error.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si10',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'hard',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nIt is high time the government [takes] strong action against financial fraudsters.',o:['took','takes','had taken','will take'],c:0,e:'"It is high time" is always followed by the past tense (subjunctive), even though the meaning is present or future: "It is high time the government TOOK strong action." Using simple present "takes" is incorrect in this construction.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si11',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe rupee has been [continuously depreciating] against the dollar for the past six months.',o:['continuously depreciating','continuous depreciating','continual depreciated','continually depreciated'],c:0,e:'"Has been depreciating" is present perfect continuous tense — used for an ongoing action that started in the past and continues. "Continuously depreciating" correctly uses the adverb form "continuously" with the present participle "depreciating." No change needed; option A preserves the original.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si12',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe bank [refrained] from making any comment on the allegations.',o:['refrained itself','refrained from','abstained from making','refraining from'],c:1,e:'"Refrain from" is the correct phrasal verb — it does not take a reflexive pronoun ("itself"). Option B "refrained from" is already correct. "Abstained from making" would work grammatically but changes the meaning slightly. The sentence as given is correct; the answer maintains "refrained from."',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si13',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'hard',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\n[Having completed] the audit, the report was submitted to the board.',o:['Having completed','After completing','When they completed','The auditors completing'],c:1,e:'The original sentence has a dangling participle — "Having completed the audit" implies the subject of the main clause (the report) completed the audit, which is illogical. "After completing the audit" still has this issue. The best correction is "After the auditors completed the audit, the report was submitted" — but among given options, "After completing" (option B) is the most acceptable standard correction used in exam contexts.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si14',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nShe is [used to work] late hours due to the workload during closing month.',o:['used to working','used to work','use to working','uses to work'],c:0,e:'"Be used to" (meaning accustomed to) is followed by a gerund (verb+ing): "used to working." Contrast with "used to + base verb" (past habit). Since the sentence describes habitual current behaviour (she is accustomed to), "used to working" is correct.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si15',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'easy',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe seminar on banking reforms will be held [in] 15th March at the RBI headquarters.',o:['at','in','on','by'],c:2,e:'For specific dates, we use the preposition "on": "on 15th March." "In" is used for months/years; "at" is used for specific times. "On 15th March" is the correct form.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si16',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'hard',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe board, [in addition to the CEO], have approved the merger proposal.',o:['in addition to the CEO, has','in addition to the CEO, have','along with CEO, have','besides the CEO, had'],c:0,e:'"The board" is the main subject (singular collective noun). Phrases introduced by "in addition to," "as well as," "together with" do not change the subject. "The board...has approved" is correct. Option A correctly uses "has" with the singular subject.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si17',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe new banking app is [convenient for use] by senior citizens.',o:['convenient to use','convenient for use','conveniently used','convenient using'],c:0,e:'"Convenient to use" (adjective + infinitive) is the standard correct construction in English. "Convenient for use" is awkward phrasing. The pattern "adjective + to + infinitive" (e.g., easy to use, difficult to understand, convenient to use) is grammatically preferred.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'si18',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nAlthough the scheme was beneficial, [but] many farmers did not apply for it.',o:['yet','but','however','No improvement needed'],c:0,e:'"Although...but" is a double conjunction error — two subordinating/coordinating conjunctions cannot anchor the same clause. "Although...yet" is an accepted literary construction in formal English. Replacing "but" with "yet" corrects the error while preserving meaning.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si19',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'hard',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nThe Finance Minister, together with his advisers, [were formulating] the new fiscal policy.',o:['was formulating','were formulating','have been formulating','are formulating'],c:0,e:'"The Finance Minister" is the singular main subject. "Together with his advisers" is a parenthetical phrase and does not change the subject number. Therefore, the singular verb "was formulating" is correct.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'si20',s:'english',t:'sentence_improvement',d:'medium',q:'Which of the following, if substituted for the underlined part, makes the sentence grammatically correct and meaningful?\n\nI wish I [have] more time to prepare for the RBI Grade B examination.',o:['had','have','would have','will have'],c:0,e:'"I wish" expresses a hypothetical or contrary-to-fact situation. It is followed by the past subjunctive: "I wish I had more time." Using present tense "have" is incorrect after "wish" when referring to a present desire. "Would have" is used for past hypotheticals.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// CLOZE TEST (ct1_1 to ct3_5) — 15 questions
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// ── CLOZE PASSAGE 1: Digital Banking Transformation ──
const CLOZE1_INTRO = `[Cloze Passage 1 — Digital Banking Transformation]\n\nThe Indian banking sector has undergone a __(1)__ transformation in recent years, driven primarily by technological innovation and regulatory support. Digital channels have __(2)__ traditional brick-and-mortar branches as the preferred mode of banking for millions of customers. The RBI's push for financial inclusion through mobile banking, internet banking, and UPI has __(3)__ access to formal financial services. Banks are now investing heavily in artificial intelligence to __(4)__ customer experience and detect fraudulent transactions. However, cybersecurity threats remain a __(5)__ concern, requiring constant upgradation of digital infrastructure.\n\n`;

Q.push(
{id:'ct1_1',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE1_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (1):\n"The Indian banking sector has undergone a __(1)__ transformation..."`,o:['marginal','profound','superficial','temporary'],c:1,e:'"Profound" means far-reaching and deep, which correctly describes the scale of transformation in Indian banking. "Marginal" and "superficial" imply minor changes (opposite meaning), while "temporary" contradicts the idea of structural change.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ct1_2',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE1_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (2):\n"Digital channels have __(2)__ traditional brick-and-mortar branches..."`,o:['supplemented','overshadowed','demolished','ignored'],c:1,e:'"Overshadowed" means to diminish the importance of something, which aptly describes how digital channels have made physical branches less prominent. "Supplemented" would mean added to (not replaced), "demolished" is too extreme, and "ignored" is inappropriate.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ct1_3',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'easy',q:`${CLOZE1_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (3):\n"...has __(3)__ access to formal financial services."`,o:['restricted','democratised','commercialised','eliminated'],c:1,e:'"Democratised" means made something available to everyone regardless of social standing — perfectly describing financial inclusion. "Restricted" is the opposite. "Commercialised" means profit-focused, and "eliminated" means removed entirely.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ct1_4',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'easy',q:`${CLOZE1_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (4):\n"Banks are now investing heavily in artificial intelligence to __(4)__ customer experience..."`,o:['degrade','enhance','monitor','restrict'],c:1,e:'"Enhance" means to improve or add value, which is the purpose of AI investment in banking — improving customer experience. "Degrade" is opposite; "monitor" and "restrict" do not fit the positive context of investment in AI for customer benefit.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ct1_5',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE1_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (5):\n"...cybersecurity threats remain a __(5)__ concern..."`,o:['trivial','persistent','resolved','technical'],c:1,e:'"Persistent" means continuing to exist despite efforts to address it — accurately describing cybersecurity threats in banking. "Trivial" means insignificant (opposite context), "resolved" means solved (contradicts "remain a concern"), and "technical" is too vague as a descriptor.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ── CLOZE PASSAGE 2: RBI's Role in Economy ──
const CLOZE2_INTRO = `[Cloze Passage 2 — RBI's Role in the Economy]\n\nThe Reserve Bank of India __(1)__ as the central bank and monetary authority of the country. It is __(2)__ for formulating and implementing monetary policy to maintain price stability. The RBI also acts as a banker to the government and __(3)__ the foreign exchange reserves of India. In times of economic __(4)__, the RBI may cut interest rates to stimulate growth or raise them to __(5)__ inflationary pressures.\n\n`;

Q.push(
{id:'ct2_1',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'easy',q:`${CLOZE2_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (1):\n"The Reserve Bank of India __(1)__ as the central bank..."`,o:['acts','acted','is acting','will act'],c:0,e:'"Acts" (simple present) is correct for stating a permanent role or institutional function. The RBI\'s role as central bank is an ongoing, established fact — simple present tense is appropriate for such universal truths.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ct2_2',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'easy',q:`${CLOZE2_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (2):\n"It is __(2)__ for formulating and implementing monetary policy..."`,o:['criticised','responsible','blamed','celebrated'],c:1,e:'"Responsible for" is the standard phrase meaning having the duty or obligation to do something. "Criticised for," "blamed for," and "celebrated for" all change the meaning entirely and are contextually inappropriate.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ct2_3',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE2_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (3):\n"...and __(3)__ the foreign exchange reserves of India."`,o:['spends','manages','liquidates','borrows'],c:1,e:'"Manages" correctly describes the RBI\'s custodial role over India\'s foreign exchange reserves. The RBI manages and maintains these reserves. "Spends" and "liquidates" imply disposing of assets, while "borrows" is contextually wrong.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ct2_4',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE2_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (4):\n"In times of economic __(4)__, the RBI may cut interest rates..."`,o:['boom','slowdown','stability','surplus'],c:1,e:'The RBI cuts interest rates to stimulate growth — this action is taken during an economic "slowdown" (when growth is sluggish). During a "boom" or "stability," rate cuts are not typical. "Surplus" refers to finances, not economic conditions.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ct2_5',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE2_INTRO}Q: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (5):\n"...or raise them to __(5)__ inflationary pressures."`,o:['encourage','address','curb','ignite'],c:2,e:'"Curb" means to control or reduce — raising interest rates is used to curb (reduce) inflationary pressures by making borrowing more expensive, thus reducing money supply. "Encourage" and "ignite" mean to increase inflation (opposite). "Address" is too vague.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// ── CLOZE PASSAGE 3: Credit Rating & Investment ──
const CLOZE3_INTRO = `[Cloze Passage 3 — Credit Rating and Investment Climate]\n\nCredit rating agencies play a __(1)__ role in the financial markets by assessing the creditworthiness of borrowers, including governments and corporations. A high credit rating __(2)__ to investors that the borrower is financially sound and likely to repay debt obligations on time. Conversely, a downgrade in credit rating can __(3)__ capital outflows and increase borrowing costs significantly. India's credit rating has remained at the lowest investment __(4)__ by global agencies such as Moody's and S&P, reflecting both its growth potential and fiscal challenges. Improving the fiscal deficit and maintaining economic __(5)__ are key factors that could lead to a rating upgrade.`;

Q.push(
{id:'ct3_1',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE3_INTRO}\n\nQ: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (1):\n"Credit rating agencies play a __(1)__ role in the financial markets..."`,o:['marginal','pivotal','decorative','temporary'],c:1,e:'"Pivotal" means critically important — credit rating agencies have a fundamentally important role in financial markets, influencing investment decisions globally. "Marginal" means minor; "decorative" and "temporary" are clearly inappropriate.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ct3_2',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'easy',q:`${CLOZE3_INTRO}\n\nQ: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (2):\n"A high credit rating __(2)__ to investors that the borrower is financially sound..."`,o:['warns','signals','conceals','denies'],c:1,e:'"Signals" means sends a clear message or indication — a high credit rating signals financial soundness to investors. "Warns" implies danger (opposite meaning in this context); "conceals" and "denies" are antonyms of the intended meaning.',x:['sbi_prelims','sbi_mains']},

{id:'ct3_3',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE3_INTRO}\n\nQ: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (3):\n"...a downgrade in credit rating can __(3)__ capital outflows..."`,o:['prevent','reverse','trigger','welcome'],c:2,e:'"Trigger" means to cause or initiate — a credit rating downgrade triggers capital outflows as investors pull funds out of a country perceived as risky. "Prevent" and "reverse" suggest reduction of outflows, which is opposite. "Welcome" is contextually absurd.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ct3_4',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'medium',q:`${CLOZE3_INTRO}\n\nQ: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (4):\n"India's credit rating has remained at the lowest investment __(4)__..."`,o:['class','grade','category','notch'],c:1,e:'In credit rating terminology, "investment grade" is the standard phrase denoting the tier of creditworthiness. "BBB-" or equivalent is typically the lowest investment grade rating. "Notch," "class," and "category" are not used in this specific financial context.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},

{id:'ct3_5',s:'english',t:'cloze_test',d:'hard',q:`${CLOZE3_INTRO}\n\nQ: Choose the most appropriate word for blank (5):\n"Improving the fiscal deficit and maintaining economic __(5)__ are key factors..."`,o:['turmoil','stagnation','resilience','inflation'],c:2,e:'"Resilience" means the ability to withstand shocks and recover — maintaining economic resilience is a positive factor that would lead to a credit rating upgrade. "Turmoil" and "stagnation" are negative conditions. "Inflation" is a challenge, not something to "maintain" positively.',x:['sbi_mains','rbi_phase1']},
);

// Total: adds ~95 questions to Q[]
